{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:22:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:22:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.04,0.73,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45345"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43885"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45345"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-month-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her mother who reports that her daughter has been vomiting over the last two weeks. The vomit is not projectile in nature. This happens with every meal and its contents are mainly milk. She used to feed the infant every four hours, but more recently has spread this out to six-hourly. She is exclusively breastfed and her mother reports normal urine output and stools. The infant has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. She is growing well and tracking along the 65th percentile on her growth charts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trial lactose-free formula","Cease oral feeds","Commence proton pump inhibitor","Smaller, more frequent feeds","Exclude dairy from mother\u0027s diet"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EReflux (vomiting) is very common immediately after feeds in infants. Such episodes are quite normal in healthy babies and do not require specific investigations or management. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmaller, more frequent feeds\u003C/strong\u003E as well as positional changes (keeping upright) can help with the regurgitation. Thickening agents can also be trialled. At this stage this is all the advice that the mother needs - together with reassurance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-feed regurgitation should be differentiated from gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) or the projectile vomiting of pyloric stenosis. In cases of GORD, symptoms usually begin before eight weeks of age and resolve by one year of age. The diagnosis of GORD might be suspected when there is poor growth, irritability, aspiration, cough or refusal to feed. In such cases, cow\u0027s milk protein exclusion and acid suppressant therapy may be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactose-free formula\u003C/strong\u003E would not ease her symptoms as lactose intolerance is unlikely in this scenario. It usually presents with watery stools and the baby would be irritable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing oral feeds\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as pyloric stenosis is less likely in this case. Pyloric stenosis usually presents in babies between 2-8 weeks of age. In pyloric stenosis, vomiting is forceful and projectile. There is also often weight loss or inadequate weight gain, which is contrary to this case. The infants tend to be dehydrated on examination, and a pyloric mass may be palpated in the right upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eproton pump inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as this is just reflux and not GORD. It should only be commenced if there are complications such as poor growth, feeding issues, aspiration, cough or wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcluding dairy from mother\u0027s diet\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as cow\u0027s milk protein allergy is less likely with normal stools. The baby would have poor weight gain and loose stools as well.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Reflux is common in infants and can be managed by simple measures such as smaller, more frequent feeds."],"references":["Davies I, Burman-Roy S, Murphy MS; Guideline Development Group. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease in children: NICE guidance. BMJ. 2015. 350:g7703.","https://www.rch.org.au/kidsinfo/fact_sheets/Reflux_GOR_and_GORD/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T18:36:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-13T18:37:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45345"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/